//Balanced Binary Tree
//Given a binary tree, determine if it is height-balanced.
//A binary tree is height-balanced if the heights of the two subtrees of every node never differ by more than 1.
//Example 1:
//Input: root = [3,9,20,null,null,15,7]
//Output: true
//Example 2:
//Input: root = [1,2,2,3,3,null,null,4,4]
//Output: false
//Example 3:
//Input: root = []
//Output: true

Brute Force Approach ->

For every node:
Calculate the height of the left subtree.
Calculate the height of the right subtree.
Check whether their difference is greater than 1.
Recursively verify that both left and right subtrees are balanced.

class Solution {
public:
    int height(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == nullptr) {
            return 0;
        }
        return 1 + max(height(root->left),
                       height(root->right));
    }
    bool isBalanced(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == nullptr) {
            return true;
        }
        int leftHeight = height(root->left);
        int rightHeight = height(root->right);
        if(abs(leftHeight - rightHeight) > 1) {
            return false;
        }
        return isBalanced(root->left) &&
               isBalanced(root->right);
    }
};

Intuition ->
For every node:
Check:
|height(left) - height(right)| <= 1
If the current node is balanced and both subtrees are balanced, then the whole tree is balanced.

Complexity Analysis ->
Time Complexity -> O(n²)
where:
n = number of nodes
Reason:
For every node, we recompute heights of subtrees.

Space Complexity -> O(h)
where:
h = height of the tree
Reason:
Recursive call stack.

Optimization Journey

The brute force solution repeatedly computes heights.
Example:

        1
       / \
      2   2
     /
    3
   /
  4

When checking node 1: 
height(2) is computed.
When checking node 2:
height(3) is computed again.
Lots of repeated work.

Key Observation
While checking balance, we already need:
height(left)
height(right)
So:
Instead of:
Compute height
Then check balance
We can:
Compute height
AND
check balance
in the same DFS traversal.

Optimal Approach -> (DFS Height + Early Failure)

class Solution {
public:
    int checkHeight(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == nullptr) {
            return 0;
        }
        int leftHeight = checkHeight(root->left);
        if(leftHeight == -1) {
            return -1;
        }
        int rightHeight = checkHeight(root->right);
        if(rightHeight == -1) {
            return -1;
        }
        if(abs(leftHeight - rightHeight) > 1) {
            return -1;
        }
        return 1 + max(leftHeight, rightHeight);
    }
    bool isBalanced(TreeNode* root) {
        return checkHeight(root) != -1;
    }
};

Complexity Analysis ->
Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes
Reason:
Every node is visited exactly once.

Space Complexity -> O(h)
where:
h = height of the tree
Reason:
Recursive call stack.

Balanced Tree:
O(log n)
Worst Case Skewed Tree:
O(n)

